eth century, the Jacobs affair. This fascinating study develops a new and improved typology of the Jewish response to modernity, and is therefore a contribution to the neglected area of Anglo-Jewish religious history, and the history of modern Judaism as a whole.It will be of interest to the student of Anglo-Jewry, of Judaism in the modern period, of the effects of modernity on religion, and general reader alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChief RabbinatezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aChief RabbinatezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aOrthodox JudaismzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aOrthodox JudaismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Jewish religious history.  aBritain.  aChief Rabbis.  aEmancipation.  aEnlightenment.  aImmanuel Jakobovits.  aJewish community.  aJoseph Herman Hertz.  aNathan Marcus Adler.  aacknowledgement school.  aaesthetic approach.  amodernity.  anostalgic approach.  apre-modern era.  areligious attitudes.  areligious policy.  aromantic approach.  ascientific approach.1 aElton, Benjamin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129963423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129963/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles